Chapter 2: Literature Review

2.1 Introduction

This chapter provides a systematic review of the literature underpinning the research framework presented in Chapter 1. The review is organised into five thematic sections. First, the Moroccan aerospace ecosystem is examined in terms of its industrial structure, human capital constraints, and strategic positioning within global value chains. Second, Morocco’s national AI and digital transformation strategies are analysed as enabling policy frameworks. Third, three international cluster models—Toulouse, Montreal and Singapore—are compared to extract transferable institutional design principles. Fourth, the technical literature on AI‑driven autonomous systems for aerospace MRO is critically assessed, focusing on drone‑based visual inspection, predictive maintenance, and hybrid CNN‑LSTM architectures for non‑destructive evaluation (NDE). Fifth, innovation policy instruments—joint labs, vouchers and skills passports—are reviewed as mechanisms for bridging the university‑industry divide. The chapter concludes by identifying the specific research gap that this thesis addresses.

2.2 The Moroccan Aerospace Ecosystem: Industrial Maturity with Structural Gaps

2.2.1 Sectoral Overview and Economic Significance

Morocco has transformed its aerospace sector from a nascent subcontracting industry into Africa’s leading manufacturing and assembly hub. As of 2025, the sector comprises approximately 150 companies concentrated in Casablanca (Midparc/Nouaceur), Tangier, Rabat and Fès, generating annual revenue of €2.5 billion (approximately $2.8 billion) and employing 26,000 full‑time workers. Exports reached MAD 26.44 billion ($2.64 billion) in 2024, a 14.9 % year‑on‑year increase, with the assembly segment alone expanding by 23.6 %. The local integration rate has risen from 18 % in 2010 to over 40 % in certain segments today, reflecting growing sophistication among domestic suppliers.

Major international players—Airbus, Boeing, Safran, Spirit AeroSystems, Collins Aerospace and Bombardier—have integrated Morocco as a strategic link in their global value chains. The sector’s competitive advantages include production costs of approximately €25 per hour (compared to €100‑120 in Europe or the United States), political stability, free trade agreements with the European Union and the United States, and proximity to European markets.

2.2.2 Recent Strategic Investments

Three recent investment announcements underscore Morocco’s growing strategic importance. In October 2025, Safran announced an investment exceeding €350 million in two new LEAP engine facilities in Casablanca: a maintenance, repair and overhaul (MRO) site (25,000 m², capacity of 150 engines annually, 600 jobs by 2030) and a LEAP‑1A assembly line (300 jobs, 350 engines annually). In February 2026, Safran further committed to a €280 million landing‑gear manufacturing facility within the Casablanca airport zone (26,000 m², 500 skilled workers, operations from 2029), powered entirely by decarbonised electricity. These investments, concentrated in the Midparc free zone, create an immediate and urgent demand for AI‑augmented quality control and inspection capabilities.

2.2.3 Human Capital Constraints

Despite the sector’s impressive growth, a structural talent bottleneck persists. Morocco produces approximately 23,000 engineering graduates annually, yet only 400 (1.7 %) enter the aeronautics sector. This mismatch is particularly acute given the sector’s transition toward advanced manufacturing, where skills in AI, robotics and data science are increasingly required. The Institut des Métiers de l’Aéronautique (IMA) trains 1,200 technicians annually with a 95 % employment rate, but its curriculum remains predominantly vocational rather than focused on Industry 4.0 competencies. Institutions such as AEROSUP (the first post‑baccalaureate aeronautical engineering school in Morocco) and UM6P’s engineering programmes produce graduates, but specialised AI‑aerospace tracks are absent from their publicly documented curricula. This gap between industrial demand and available talent is a recurring theme in the literature on emerging aerospace clusters (Armellini et al., 2011) and is identified as a primary barrier to value‑chain upgrading in developing economies (Ernst, 2016).

2.2.4 Literature Gap: Descriptive versus Prescriptive Studies

The existing academic literature on Moroccan aerospace is predominantly descriptive. Studies have documented the sector’s evolution, foreign investment patterns and export performance (e.g., El Aoufi & Bensaïd, 2012; Labaronne & Roux, 2017), but no peer‑reviewed research has proposed a quantified, executable roadmap for integrating AI‑driven autonomous systems into MRO or manufacturing operations. Furthermore, the literature has not distinguished between what a single PhD project can deliver versus what the broader ecosystem must implement—a distinction critical for realistic research design. This thesis responds to that gap.

2.3 National AI and Digital Transformation Strategies

2.3.1 Maroc Digital 2030 and the National AI Roadmap

Morocco has established a comprehensive policy framework to support digital transformation. The “Maroc Digital 2030” strategy, launched in 2024, aims to modernise public services and digital infrastructure (Ministry of Digital Transition, 2024). Building on this foundation, the “Maroc IA 2030” (AI Made in Morocco) national AI strategy was launched on 12 January 2026, targeting a $10 billion contribution to GDP and the creation of 240,000 digital jobs by 2030, including 50,000 jobs directly linked to AI.

A centrepiece of the strategy is the establishment of a national network of “Al‑Jazari Institutes”—regional centres of excellence designed to link academic research with industrial deployment. The Al‑Jazari Institute for Industry X.0 was inaugurated in Fès in March 2026, with priority domains including the Internet of Things, advanced robotics, production data analytics, and predictive maintenance. The Dakhla Al‑Jazari Institute will specialise in AI and energy transition, while a central “JAZARI ROOT” institute focuses on digital sovereignty and data science.

The strategy also emphasises technological sovereignty, including the development of sovereign cloud infrastructure and the planned 500 MW “Dakhla AI Battery” green data centre, which will provide renewable‑powered compute capacity for large‑scale AI model training. International partnerships have been established, including a cooperation agreement with Mistral AI to establish a joint R&D laboratory.

2.3.2 Sovereign Compute Infrastructure

The UM6P “Toubkal” supercomputer, Africa’s most powerful, provides the necessary infrastructure for training large‑scale AI models without reliance on international cloud providers. Toubkal supports a diverse range of workloads—from tightly coupled MPI simulations to modern large‑scale AI training—and combines free cooling with a 1 MW solar power plant for energy efficiency. The supercomputer is accessible to Moroccan researchers and has been used for hands‑on training workshops for master’s students and PhD candidates.

2.3.3 Regulatory Framework for Civilian Drones

A critical regulatory development for this research is the draft decree on civilian drones prepared by the Directorate General for Civil Aviation (DGAC). As of October 2025, the draft decree has been submitted to the General Secretariat of the Government for finalisation. The decree establishes a specific regulatory framework for the design, production, maintenance and operation of unmanned aircraft, requiring a certificate issued by the DGAC for all relevant activities. However, as of mid‑2026, civilian drone operations remain heavily restricted in Morocco, with the general rule being that importation, possession and use of drones are prohibited. This regulatory uncertainty is a significant risk for this research, which the methodology (Chapter 3) addresses through a contingency plan.

2.3.4 Literature Gap: Implementation Readiness

While policy documents articulate ambitious goals, the academic literature has not yet examined the implementation readiness of Morocco’s AI strategy for industrial applications. Questions regarding the translation of national AI policy into sector‑specific roadmaps (e.g., for aerospace), the operationalisation of Al‑Jazari Institutes as joint research platforms, and the mechanisms for SME engagement remain unexplored. This research contributes to filling this gap by proposing concrete implementation instruments aligned with national policy.

2.4 Global Cluster Models for Aerospace Innovation

2.4.1 Montreal: The Triple Helix Model

The Montreal aerospace cluster, comprising approximately 206 companies, is widely cited in the literature as a successful example of “triple helix” collaboration—integrating university, industry and government stakeholders to drive disruptive innovation (Armellini et al., 2011; Koschatzky & Kroll, 2007). Montreal is the only location globally where an entire aircraft can be assembled from locally manufactured components, supported by an R&D environment that accounts for more than 70 % of Canadian aerospace R&D spending. The triple helix model emphasises “circulation” of knowledge and personnel among the three spheres, facilitated by dedicated cluster organisations such as Aéro Montréal, which serve as neutral convenors for collaborative projects.

For Morocco, the triple helix model offers a relevant template because it does not depend on the presence of a dominant OEM. Instead, it enables decentralised but coordinated innovation among numerous SMEs and large firms—a structural feature shared by Morocco’s GIMAS network. However, the literature notes that successful triple helix implementation requires sustained government commitment, patient capital, and intermediary organisations capable of managing intellectual property across partners (Etzkowitz & Leydesdorff, 2000).

2.4.2 Singapore: The A*STAR Joint Lab Model

Singapore’s Agency for Science, Technology and Research (A*STAR) provides an alternative model focused on public‑private joint laboratories. The Advanced Remanufacturing and Technology Centre (ARTC) operates a “Model Factory” that serves as a living laboratory where industry partners, SMEs and public researchers co‑develop and test‑bed Industry 4.0 technologies before adoption.

A notable example relevant to this thesis is the S$60 million joint lab established by A*STAR, Rolls‑Royce and Singapore Aero Engine Services (SAESL) to develop next‑generation aerospace MRO capabilities enabled by advanced processes, automation and digital technologies. The lab comprises five thematic areas: smart assembly systems, integrated remanufacturing technologies, advanced fan blade manufacturing, future manufacturing processes, and knowledge‑based manufacturing using Industry 4.0 methods. Critically, the Model Factory initiative includes explicit mechanisms for SME engagement, allowing smaller firms to test new technologies with the help of public sector researchers before committing to adoption.

The Singaporean model is directly transferable to Morocco because it was designed for a small, open economy seeking to move up the value chain from manufacturing to innovation. Unlike the OEM‑centric Toulouse model, it does not require a dominant local anchor firm. However, the literature notes that A*STAR’s success depended on sustained public investment (approximately S$2 billion annually in R&D) and a long‑term policy horizon—conditions that Morocco is only beginning to establish.

2.4.3 Toulouse: The OEM‑Centric Model

The Toulouse cluster, dominated by Airbus, represents a top‑down model where innovation is driven primarily by the OEM’s supplier development programmes and procurement requirements (Grossetti & Bès, 2003). While highly successful, this model is less directly transferable to Morocco because no single Moroccan firm has the procurement power of Airbus. However, Toulouse offers lessons in sustainability and certification—areas where Airbus has invested heavily in AI for quality assurance and predictive maintenance.

2.4.4 Synthesis: Design Principles for Morocco

From these three models, the following design principles for the proposed Integrated Research Unit (IRU) are extracted:

Design Principle Source Model Relevance to Morocco
Co‑location of researchers with industry engineers Singapore (ARTC) Reduces technology transfer friction; enables tacit knowledge exchange
Neutral convenor organisation (e.g., GIMAS, AMC) Montreal (Aéro Montréal) Manages IP and coordinates among diverse partners
Model factory / living laboratory Singapore (ARTC) Allows low‑risk testing of new technologies before adoption
